diff:1670566688:1670110644:=62,80c62%0a%3c #foxbegin 221209-061808-473060#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Causatives by Juxtaposition in Navajo %0a%3c -> - akshaychekuri%0a%3c -> [-08.12.2022 - 22:18-]%0a%3c >>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a%3c (:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c {[foxdelrange button 221209-061808-473060 {$FullName} ]}%0a%3c (:if1end:)%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c While looking for a way to expand on this article, I happened upon an interesting paper regarding causatives in the Navajo language. For some background, a causative expression involves a cause and a result. An example would be "I ate because I was hungry". The Navajo language uses similar constructions for causative expressions. The language has a morpheme that is synonymous with "because" and is used similarly, as described in this paper. %0a%3c %0a%3c More interestingly, the Navajo language can imply a causative expression through juxtaposition. For example, the sentence "bil nisaa iixazh", which literally translates to "Sleepiness I knew I went to sleep" actually means "I went to bed because I was sleepy". The juxtaposition exists because there are two clauses presented in the sentence without a conjunction, but it is implied that the second event happened as a result of the first. These causatives are used most often for "internal forces" such as sleepiness, hunger or thirst.%0a%3c %0a%3c Source: https://www.linguistics.ucsb.edu/sites/secure.lsit.ucsb.edu.ling.d7/files/sitefiles/research/papers/18/Goertz.et_.al_._vol18.pdf%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 221209-061808-473060#%0a---%0a> %0a
